pr_review_comment_body:
Since this is just a single classmethod, I would make it a simple factory-method; this make extra sense with the above changes.

Also I would make it "private" since nothing should be creating errors besides code in here:

```
def _create_socks_error(code):
    try:
        return _socks_errors[code]()
    except KeyError:
        return SocksError(code=code, message="Unknown SOCKS error-code {}".format(code))
```

Well, that exact code above would need a little more smarts in SocksError's ``__init__``

I guess you can also see I think I prefer "code" or similar to "errno" (so we aren't "conflicting" with the popular C global variable name). Also, I prefer catching KeyError over "check, then access" when doing dict stuff (there's another one you did with the "check-first" way above).

All of changes in this file could be drastically simplified. I am thinking along these lines:

```python
for seg_conf in config["segments"]:
    if not isinstance(seg_conf, dict):
        seg_conf = {"type": seg_conf}
    mod = importlib.import_module("powerline_shell.segments." + seg_conf["type"])
    segment = getattr(mod, "Segment")(powerline, seg_conf.get("options"))
```

This should be all that's needed (at least in this file). This does require changing the segment classes to all accept an "options" argument. But you could also avoid that in this PR by changing my last line to:

```python
    if "options" in seg_conf:
        segment = getattr(mod, "Segment")(powerline, seg_conf["options"])
    else:
        segment = getattr(mod, "Segment")(powerline)
```

@tjprescott There was a reason we has the install of requirements last.
It was to prevent command modules that are installed later from overriding what we have in requirements.txt.
It was with `azure-mgmt-keyvault` back when we were using the `azure` rollup package.

@troydai Is this particular change required for this fix to work?

